Clustering Analysis on Gene Expressions¶

Chesie Yu

2/15/2023

Clustering analysis allows us to uncover the underlying structure embedded in gene expression profiles: identifying groups of samples sharing similar expression patterns can help understanding gene functions and disease subtypes.

In this notebook, we will perform clustering on gene expression data to identify patterns associated with various cancer subtypes (BRCA, LUAD, COAD, KIRC, PRAD), by applying $K$-means and hierarchical algorithms to segment the data into homogenous subgroups. The dataset contains 801 samples and 20,531 attributes, representing gene expression levels of patients having different types of tumors. It is part of the RNA-Seq PANCAN data set, and can be accessed from UCI Machine Learning Repository.

2. $K$-Means Clustering¶

First, we will use $K$-means clustering to find homogeneous subgroups of tumors among samples, by partitioning the dataset into desired number of $K$ distinct clusters.

Intuitively, variation will continue to decrease as $K$ increases. But adding more clusters does not necessarily improve clustering quality: it may not be able to capture the true underlying structure of the data. Therefore we need to determine the optimal $K$ using the elbow method: by visualizing the losses as a function of $K$, we can identify the elbow point where adding more clusters will no longer significantly improve clustering performance.

In [11]:
# Create empty list of losses
losses = []

# Create a list of k values
ks = range(1, 16)

# Compute the loss for each k 
for k in ks:
    m = KMeans(n_clusters = k, n_init = 20).fit(X)
    losses.append(m.inertia_)
    
# Create the elbow plot: Plot losses as a function of k
_ = plt.plot(ks, losses, marker = "o", color = "#4393C3")
_ = plt.title("Elbow Plot for K-Means Clustering")
_ = plt.xlabel("Number of Clusters (K)")
_ = plt.ylabel("Loss")

Once the optimal number of clusters $K = 5$ is identified, we can apply the $K$-means clustering algorithm:

In [12]:

2.1 Evaluation¶

To evaluate the $K$-means clustering results, we can compute the inertia, measured as the sum of squared distances between each data point and its centroid. In general, our objective is to minimize the within cluster variation $C_k$ so that the elements within a cluster would be as similar as possible.

In [14]:
# Compute the loss
m.inertia_
Out[14]:
17801949.109766014

However, given the original labels, a better approach would be using external criteria to assess the clustering performance. Here we will report the Adjusted Rand Index (ARI) and Normalized Mutual Information (NMI).

ARI measures the similarity between two assignments within range [-1, 1]; it is adjusted for chance so that random labeling will be assigned an ARI score close to zero

NMI is an information theoretic measure of cluster quality; it quantifies the shared information between clusterings. NMI ranges from 0 to 1, with 1 indicating perfectly identical assignments and 0 suggesting random assignments with no mutual information.

As shown below, both ARI and NMI scores are very close to 1, indicating a near perfect match.

In [15]:
# Compute ARI and NMI
from sklearn.metrics import adjusted_rand_score, normalized_mutual_info_score
ari = adjusted_rand_score(y, km_cluster)
nmi = normalized_mutual_info_score(y, km_cluster)
print(f"ARI: {ari:.3f}\nNMI: {nmi:.3f}")

ARI: 0.981
NMI: 0.972

2.2 Visualization¶

Clusters formed on high-dimensional data can be hard to visualize. An alternative approach would be to create a two-dimensional representation of the dataset using Principal Component Analysis (PCA). Through dimensionality reduction, we can visualize high dimensional clusters using only the two largest components while still retaining some of the original information: the plot below illustrates 5 distinct clusters in the data.

In [18]:
# Import PCA library
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA

# Perform dimensionality reduction
m = PCA(n_components = 2).fit(X)
X_pca = m.transform(X)

# Transform cluster center
center_pca = m.transform(center)
In [19]:
# Visualize the clustering result
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (6, 6))
ax.scatter(X_pca[:, 0], X_pca[:, 1], c = km_cluster, 
               edgecolor = "black", alpha = 0.25)
ax.scatter(center_pca[:, 0], center_pca[:, 1], c = np.unique(km_cluster),
            s = 100, alpha = 0.75, edgecolor = "black")
ax.set_aspect("equal")
ax.set_title("K-Means Clustering (K = 5)", size = 13.5)
ax.set_xlabel("PC1")
ax.set_ylabel("PC2")
plt.show()

Alternatively, we can visualize multivariate numerical data using a parallel coordinate plot: the variables are represented by axes placed parallel to each other while the observations are plotted as lines connected across all axes.

In [20]:

plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor = (1.05, 1), loc = "upper left")
plt.show()


3. Hierarchical Clustering¶

Now we will implement hierarchical clustering on the gene expression data using various linkages: complete, average, and single. This method uses a bottom-up agglomerative approach by fusing similar observations into branches; the earlier the fusion occurs, the more similar the observations are. By fusing the genes that are close to each other, we will form a hierarchical representation of the clusters.

In [21]:
# Specify the linkage methods
linkage_methods = ["complete", "average", "single"]

# Perform hierarchical clustering with different linkages
hc_cluster = {}
for method in linkage_methods:
    hc_cluster[method] = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters = 5, linkage = method).fit_predict(X)
{key: value[:10] for key, value in hc_cluster.items()}

# Set up the subplots
fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, len(linkage_methods), figsize = (18, 9))
colors = ["#2166AC", "#4393C3", "#92C5DE", "#D1E5F0", "#FDDBC7", "#F4A582", "#D6604D", "#B2182B"]

# Visualize each linkage method
for i, method in enumerate(linkage_methods):
    # Create the linkage matrix
    Z = linkage(X, method)
    # Create the dendrogram
    dendrogram(Z, ax = axs[i], color_threshold = 0.83 * max(Z[:, 2]), 
               p = 200, truncate_mode = "lastp", 
               leaf_font_size = 6, leaf_rotation = 90)
    axs[i].set_title(f"Dendrogram ({method.capitalize()} Linkage)")
    axs[i].set_xlabel("Index")
    axs[i].set_ylabel(f"Distance ({method.capitalize()} Linkage)")

# Display the plot
fig.suptitle("Hierarchical Clustering Dendrograms", size = 24)
plt.show()

Hierarchical clustering results can be visualized using dendrograms. As we can see, the result varies by choice of dissimilarity measure: hierarchical clustering with complete and average linkage produces the same cluster assignments as $K$-means clustering; on the other hand, single linkage yields imbalanced classes by grouping almost all observations into the same cluster.

In [24]:
# Compute ARI and NMI
for m in hc_cluster: 
    ari = adjusted_rand_score(y, hc_cluster[m])
    nmi = normalized_mutual_info_score(y, hc_cluster[m])
    print(f"{m.capitalize()} Linkage:\nARI: {ari:.3f}\nNMI: {nmi:.3f}\n")

Complete Linkage:
ARI: 0.849
NMI: 0.856

Average Linkage:
ARI: -0.008
NMI: 0.023

Single Linkage:
ARI: 0.000
NMI: 0.010

Result shows that $K$-means clustering produces a partition that closely aligns with the underlying structure in the data. Both the ARI and NMI are very close to 1, suggesting that the clusters are well represented.

On the other hand, hierarchical clustering yielded lower performance. Among the three linkage methods tested, complete linkage performed fairly well with ARI and NMI greater than 0.8, capturing some of the cluster structure. However, clustering based on average and single linkage provided less than satisfactory results: almost all genes are grouped into the same cluster.

This result aligns with the findings in numerous comparative studies on gene expression clusterings: $K$-means tends to "outperform hierarchical clustering"$^{[1]}$; "single linkage presents the worse results"$^{[2]}$ within the class of hierarchical methods.

[1] D'haeseleer, P. How does gene expression clustering work?. Nat Biotechnol 23, 1499–1501 (2005). https://doi.org/10.1038/nbt1205-1499

[2] de Souto, M.C., Costa, I.G., de Araujo, D.S. et al. Clustering cancer gene expression data: a comparative study. BMC Bioinformatics 9, 497 (2008). https://doi.org/10.1186/1471-2105-9-497

Limitations¶

There are several limitations with the two clustering methods. Clustering results are sensitive to outliers and noise in the data; the clusters may not be as representative with the presence of outliers. Without knowing the ground truth, model evaluation is often limited to using dissimilarity measurements for internal validation.

In $K$-means clustering, the result will vary with our choice of number of clusters, and this decision is relatively subjective even with the help from elbow plots. Moreover, $K$-means clustering is sensitive to initial conditions: different initializations can lead to different results, and it could therefore converge to a local optimum instead of global optimum.

For hierarchical clustering, our choice of linkage method can have significant impacts on the results. Just as the case above, single and average linkages may yield significantly worse results with highly imbalanced classes. Hierarchical clustering is also conducted based on local decisions: it merges the most compact cluster available at each step, therefore would result in a potentially suboptimal solution.

# Create empty list of ARI and NMI
ari = []
nmi = []

# Create a list of n_component values
n_components = range(1, 50)

# Compute the loss for each k 
for nc in n_components:
    # Fit PCA
    X_pca = PCA(n_components = nc).fit_transform(X)
    # Fit K-means clustering and extract the cluster assignments
    km_cluster = KMeans(n_clusters = 5, n_init = 50).fit_predict(X_pca)
    # Record ARI and NMI
    ari.append(adjusted_rand_score(y, km_cluster))
    nmi.append(normalized_mutual_info_score(y, km_cluster))
    
# Plot number of components against each metric
